Overview

Over the past few years, innovation in fintech has allowed for creative ways for smaller players to make an impact with their capital: platforms like Kickstarter, GoFundMe, and Indiegogo have allowed individuals to make small contributions to business ideas, fundraisers, and other ventures. In 2005, Kiva was founded, using similar technology to allow people to make microloans to businesses and families in developing areas. This method of lending, called microfinance, has drawn supporters for making social impact more accessible for typical individuals and critics for having minimal impact. This study will investigate how loans are made on Kiva, and if these dollars are truly making a difference for people in developing countries.

This project will piggyback off of the homework case study on Lending Club, for we may cite some of the findings or intuitions gained from that study in our analysis of Kivas business.

Methods

We will use extensive EDA to get a sense of the variables in the data. We will explore questions such as which countries or latitude/longitude regions receive the most loans, what is the behavior of common borrowers/lenders on the site, breakdown demographics/gender, etc. We will provide graphics to give evidence for potential answers. We may also identify particularly corrupt or different behavior of loans from a certain MFI partner of Kiva.

We will start with unsupervised machine learning methods like clustering on the data; this will tell us if there are particular patterns that we should further explore in supervised ML methods like regression. We may need to use PCA or apply an L1/L2 penalty to reduce the dimensions of the data if it seems the model is too complex. Maintaining interpretability is important here, since we would like to know how Kivas loans are making an impact; thus, we may start with linear regression, so we can draw some insights about some features from their coefficients. Once we gain some insight about the features, we may try more robust methods for prediction, including logistic regression, neural networks, random forests (with/without boosting), or a combination of them all via bagging.

#merge loans with locations

loan_locations <- loans %>%
  select(country, funded_amount, loan_amount, term_in_months) %>%
  group_by(country) %>%
  summarise(
    avg_funded_amount = mean(funded_amount),
    avg_loan_amount = mean(loan_amount),
    avg_term_in_months = mean(term_in_months)
  ) %>%
  inner_join(locations, by = "country")

Clustering

Kmeans clustering! Chose 4 clusters

wss <- function(df, k) {
  kmeans(df, k, nstart = 10)$tot.withinss
}
k.values <- 2:9
wss.values <- sapply(k.values, function(k) kmeans(merged2[,-37], centers = k)$
                       tot.withinss)
plot(k.values, wss.values, type = "b", pch = 19, frame = FALSE, 
     xlab = "Number of clusters", ylab = "Total within-clusters sum of squares")

PCA analysis: choose 2 PCs for easiness of interpretation

kivacountry.pca <- prcomp(merged2 %>% select(-country), scale = T)
kivacountry_cluster <- kmeans(kivacountry.pca$x[, 1:2], centers = 4)

Regression Subset

Thus, we go to a simpler model (regression subset) to explore variables that may explain the loan_amount Using Cp, we found 11 variables

regkiva <- regsubsets(loan_amount~(.-country), nvmax = 35, method = "exhau", 
                      merged2)
plot(summary(regkiva)$cp)

regkiva.1.s <- summary(regkiva)
opt.size <- 11
regkiva.var.1 <- regkiva.1.s$which
var.min.reg <- colnames(regkiva.var.1)[regkiva.var.1[opt.size, ]][-1]

Exploring model fitting

See a summary of the model and see how well the model explains the loan_amount. We spotted some large residuals. 43 and 44 are Peru and Philippines. They receive much more loans than other countries so the model doesnt explain them well. Explore 54, Uganda, which has many countries that receive similar loans. Why does Uganda fail to fit in the model?

By comparing Uganda and countries that have similar loan_amounts, we see that Uganda spends less on agriculture, and much more funds on education, which is not covered by the variables in the model index. By looking at the uses of education sector funding, we see that the fundings cover school tuition, and this is not measured by the model, which could be a limitation.

Uganda = loans %>% filter(country == "Uganda") %>% 
group_by(sector) %>% summarise(n= sum(loan_amount)) %>% arrange(-n)

ggplot(Uganda, aes(x = "", y = n, fill = sector)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", width = 1) +
  coord_polar("y", start = 0) +
  theme_void() +
  labs(fill = "sector", title = "Uganda activities")

UgandaEducation = loans %>% filter(country == "Uganda", sector == "Education") %>%
  summarise(use= use, n = loan_amount) %>% arrange(-n)
